{"title":"MaPLe: Multi-modal Prompt Learning","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Prompt learning for CLIP typically tunes only the text branch, leaving the image encoder unadapted. This partial (uni-modal) adaptation limits alignment between vision and language spaces and hurts few-shot generalization to novel classes and datasets.","method":"MaPLe performs multi-modal prompt learning by inserting learnable context tokens into both CLIP’s language and vision transformers. It uses hierarchical (deep) prompting, adding prompts to the first J transformer blocks in each branch to progressively adapt stage-wise features, while keeping all original CLIP weights frozen. This joint, branch-aware prompting adapts both representation spaces for improved V-L alignment and generalization."},{"problem":"Naively learning prompts in both branches independently offers no cross-modal interaction, resulting in weak synergy between vision and language prompts and suboptimal alignment.","method":"MaPLe introduces a vision–language coupling function F that explicitly conditions the vision prompts on the language prompts per layer, via a linear projection ˜P_k = F_k(P_k) from text to vision dimensions. This bridge enables mutual gradient flow and shared embedding space across modalities, promoting synergy. Compared to independent V–L prompting, this coupling yields better generalization (e.g., higher HM on 11 datasets)."},{"problem":"Shallow prompting at only the input layer cannot capture the stage-wise contextual relationships needed to effectively adapt frozen transformer features, limiting robustness under distribution shifts.","method":"MaPLe learns separate prompts across multiple early transformer blocks (depth J) in both branches (deep prompting), and in the vision branch shares prompts across stages to exploit correlated features. Only the prompts (and the V–L coupling) are trained. Ablations show performance improves with depth and peaks at J=9, boosting base-to-novel generalization and robustness under cross-dataset and domain shifts."}]}
